Some initial exploratory notes about JavaFX
===========================================

The main challenge with JavaFX is how to handle map rendering, because
almost all the tutorials I can find assume that the application is
graphical-in-name-only with just styledtext boxes and perhaps some
static images or (also static) geometric shapes.

Serge Rosmorduc has done some work on how to render an infinite
component with JavaFX.

   https://comp.qenherkhopeshef.org/blog/javafx-large-components

The map layer can be rendered to javafx.scene.image.WritableImage and
then put into an ImageView in the JavaFX scene tree, with the inventory
managed by something like the approach above.

javafx.scene.layout.Pane can be used for absolute position of child
nodes within the map view.

The basic support for working with individual pixels is documented by
Oracle in 'the ImageOps API':

   https://docs.oracle.com/javafx/2/image_ops/jfxpub-image_ops.pdf
   https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/graphics-tutorial/image_ops.htm

However, a better way to do cross-thread rendering may be to create
the WritableImage with a javafx.scene.image.PixelBuffer, which is
documented as

> When the Buffer is updated using the PixelBuffer.updateBuffer
> method, all WritableImages that were created using this PixelBuffer
> are redrawn.

The updateBuffer method takes a callback that returns a dirty region.
and must be called in the UI thread, but given Java's memory model
it's hard to see how it could do actual damage to pre-modify the
underlying buffer in a diffent thread, and then call updateBuffer with
a do-nothing callback.

 -- Looking at gh/openjdk/jfx sources, it looks like the automatic
    redrawing is mediated by a hidden "property" of the image, defined
    at Image.platformImagePropertyImpl().

Possibly use the "animation timer" approach of

   https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26082732/what-approach-should-i-use-for-javafx-canvas-multithreading

to coordinate how often the update callback is called -- but I don't
think that ought to be necessary.

----

Despite the name, javafx.scene.canvas.Canvas is _not_ for the pixel
data, but should be a good model for the vector layers and vector
overlays. Perhaps create one for each chain and stack them in a
javafx.scene.layout.StackPane.

All the coordinates are doubles, so in principle we could do
everything in raw local coordinates. On the other hand, that may make
things blink more than they ought to when we change projection and map
tiles take some time to load? Might be better to keep an offset
mehchanism like the one we use for Swing. Canvases for the vector
layer need to be remade when the offset changes, but that is _less_
work than a Swing painting operation should be okay.

---

From JavaFX 9.0 the Window class has renderScaleXProperty() and
renderScaleYProperty(), which might be used to make the the map
rendering bitmap have device pixel scale (especially with a view to
looking nice in non-integer render scales).
